That the general principle was only gradually developed is clear from a comparison oi Dig. tp 5. 5. 3 with 9. 15 and 22 os the same Title, and with Cod. 2. 4 6; in the first os these passages Paulus says the actio praescriptis verbis will not lie in a caseos facio ut des, in the others it is held applicable, so that probably it may be inferred that for some while only those agreements were eniorceable by this remedy in which the past performance by which the action was supported was a conveyance (dare). ,

The commonest examples of innominate contract are permutatio, erchange, sor which see Tit. 23. 2 inin: aestimatum, the acceptance of property valued at a certain maximum under the condition of either retuming it or paying the price at which it is valued: ‘actio de aestimato proponitur tollendae dubitationis gratia, fuit enim magis dubitatum cum res aestimata vendenda datur, utrum err vendito sit actio propter aesti- mationem, an ex locato, quasi rem vendendam locasse videar, an ex conducto, quasi operas conduxissem, an mandati: melius itaque visum est, hanc actionem proponit quoties enim de nomine contractus am· bigeretur‚ conveniret tamen aliquam actionem dari, dandam aestima- toriam praescriptis verbis actionem' Dig. 19. 13. 1. pr.: transactio or compromise, Dig. 2. 15, Cod. 2. 4, and precarium or permissive oc- cupancy, at any rate in the later stages os the law: ‘cum quid precario rogatum est, non solum interdicto uti possumus, sed et incerti con· dictione, id est, praescriptis verbis' Dig. 43. 26. 19. 2.
